<body region="r1">
<div>
<p begin="00:00:00.000" end="00:00:01.980" style="s2">Here in this presentation, we will discuss</p>
<p begin="00:00:01.980" end="00:00:04.160" style="s2">different types of data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:00:04.160" end="00:00:05.940" style="s2">So, let&#39;s get started.</p>
<p begin="00:00:06.560" end="00:00:08.600" style="s2">Here, we have two types of data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:00:08.600" end="00:00:10.600" style="s2">One is linear data structures</p>
<p begin="00:00:10.600" end="00:00:13.440" style="s2">and the other one is non linear data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:00:13.440" end="00:00:15.680" style="s2">So, let&#39;s discuss them one by one.</p>
<p begin="00:00:16.140" end="00:00:18.700" style="s2">A data structure is linear when all the elements</p>
<p begin="00:00:18.700" end="00:00:22.380" style="s2">are arranged in a linear or sequential order.</p>
<p begin="00:00:22.380" end="00:00:25.080" style="s2">If the elements are arranged in a linear order</p>
<p begin="00:00:25.180" end="00:00:27.000" style="s2">or sequential order, then we can say that</p>
<p begin="00:00:27.060" end="00:00:29.120" style="s2">a data structure is a linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:00:29.120" end="00:00:34.100" style="s2">For example, we have arrays, <br />queues, linked lists and stacks.</p>
<p begin="00:00:34.100" end="00:00:38.240" style="s2">These data structures are <br />all linear data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:00:38.240" end="00:00:40.240" style="s2">There is one more way we can say that a</p>
<p begin="00:00:40.240" end="00:00:42.760" style="s2">particular data structure <br />is a linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:00:42.760" end="00:00:45.460" style="s2">When each element of the data structure</p>
<p begin="00:00:45.460" end="00:00:48.360" style="s2">has only one predecessor and one successor,</p>
<p begin="00:00:48.360" end="00:00:51.580" style="s2">then we can say that -- that data <br />structure is a linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:00:51.580" end="00:00:53.340" style="s2">We can see in this example that,</p>
<p begin="00:00:53.340" end="00:00:58.420" style="s2">each element is having only one <br />predecessor and one successor</p>
<p begin="00:00:58.420" end="00:01:00.600" style="s2">Here you can see this element has only</p>
<p begin="00:01:00.600" end="00:01:02.800" style="s2">one predecessor and one successor.</p>
<p begin="00:01:02.800" end="00:01:05.320" style="s2">Right? Although there is one exception also.</p>
<p begin="00:01:05.320" end="00:01:08.360" style="s2">The first element and the last <br />elements, you can see clearly.</p>
<p begin="00:01:08.360" end="00:01:10.360" style="s2">First element has no predecessor</p>
<p begin="00:01:10.360" end="00:01:12.160" style="s2">and last element has no successor.</p>
<p begin="00:01:12.160" end="00:01:13.360" style="s2">So, this is an exception,</p>
<p begin="00:01:13.360" end="00:01:15.100" style="s2">although each and every element</p>
<p begin="00:01:15.100" end="00:01:17.380" style="s2">of the data structure has this property,</p>
<p begin="00:01:17.380" end="00:01:20.480" style="s2">that is, each element has one <br />predecessor and one successor.</p>
<p begin="00:01:20.480" end="00:01:23.320" style="s2">Now, let&#39;s discuss non linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:01:24.000" end="00:01:26.180" style="s2">A data structure is non linear when</p>
<p begin="00:01:26.180" end="00:01:28.380" style="s2">all the elements are not arranged</p>
<p begin="00:01:28.380" end="00:01:30.800" style="s2">in a linear or sequential order.</p>
<p begin="00:01:30.800" end="00:01:33.280" style="s2">There is no linear <br />arrangement of the elements.</p>
<p begin="00:01:33.280" end="00:01:36.120" style="s2">For example, here we can take this data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:01:36.120" end="00:01:38.780" style="s2">This is a tree data structure, <br />as I have labeled over here.</p>
<p begin="00:01:38.780" end="00:01:41.760" style="s2">This data structure is not linear.</p>
<p begin="00:01:41.760" end="00:01:45.100" style="s2">Why we are saying that, this <br />data structure is non linear?</p>
<p begin="00:01:45.100" end="00:01:47.100" style="s2">You can see here that each node</p>
<p begin="00:01:47.100" end="00:01:49.840" style="s2">does not have one predecessor and one successor.</p>
<p begin="00:01:49.840" end="00:01:51.840" style="s2">You can see here that -- this node has</p>
<p begin="00:01:51.840" end="00:01:55.120" style="s2">one predecessor but it doesn&#39;t have one successor.</p>
<p begin="00:01:55.120" end="00:01:57.460" style="s2">It has two successors, right?</p>
<p begin="00:01:57.460" end="00:01:59.920" style="s2">So, it is clear from this fact that, this data structure</p>
<p begin="00:01:59.920" end="00:02:03.320" style="s2">is not a linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:02:03.320" end="00:02:05.760" style="s2">We have another example, that is graph.</p>
<p begin="00:02:05.760" end="00:02:08.400" style="s2">Graph is also a non linear data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:02:08.400" end="00:02:10.400" style="s2">After understanding the difference between </p>
<p begin="00:02:10.400" end="00:02:13.080" style="s2">a linear data structure and <br />a non linear data structure,</p>
<p begin="00:02:13.080" end="00:02:14.560" style="s2">let&#39;s even go further.</p>
<p begin="00:02:14.560" end="00:02:16.560" style="s2">We can make even further distinction.</p>
<p begin="00:02:16.900" end="00:02:20.180" style="s2">We do have static data structures <br />and dynamic data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:02:20.180" end="00:02:21.800" style="s2">Let&#39;s discuss them one by one.</p>
<p begin="00:02:21.800" end="00:02:23.800" style="s2">In these type of data structure,</p>
<p begin="00:02:23.800" end="00:02:26.440" style="s2">the memory is allocated at compile time.</p>
<p begin="00:02:26.440" end="00:02:28.960" style="s2">So, static data structures <br />are those data structures</p>
<p begin="00:02:28.960" end="00:02:32.360" style="s2">where the memory is allocated at compile time.</p>
<p begin="00:02:32.360" end="00:02:34.360" style="s2">Therefore, maximum size is fixed.</p>
<p begin="00:02:34.840" end="00:02:37.020" style="s2">The advantage of such data structure is that,</p>
<p begin="00:02:37.020" end="00:02:39.440" style="s2">we can access data very fast.</p>
<p begin="00:02:39.440" end="00:02:41.600" style="s2">But on the other hand, disadvantage is that</p>
<p begin="00:02:41.600" end="00:02:44.260" style="s2">insertion and deletion operations are slower.</p>
<p begin="00:02:44.260" end="00:02:45.840" style="s2">We can take an example like this.</p>
<p begin="00:02:45.840" end="00:02:48.400" style="s2">Array data structure is a static data structure,</p>
<p begin="00:02:48.400" end="00:02:51.660" style="s2">here you can see that, we <br />have to fix the size beforehand.</p>
<p begin="00:02:51.660" end="00:02:54.060" style="s2">That is why, we are fixing the size at</p>
<p begin="00:02:54.060" end="00:02:57.460" style="s2">compilation time, that is when <br />we are creating the code.</p>
<p begin="00:02:57.460" end="00:03:00.980" style="s2">Maximum size is always fixed in the case of arrays.</p>
<p begin="00:03:00.980" end="00:03:04.140" style="s2">Advantage is obviously that, we <br />can access the elements very fast,</p>
<p begin="00:03:04.140" end="00:03:06.140" style="s2">but slower insertion and deletion.</p>
<p begin="00:03:06.140" end="00:03:08.880" style="s2">We will discuss this, why <br />this disadvantage is there</p>
<p begin="00:03:08.880" end="00:03:11.540" style="s2">and why this advantage is there later.</p>
<p begin="00:03:11.540" end="00:03:13.540" style="s2">Right now, you should understand this point,</p>
<p begin="00:03:13.540" end="00:03:15.880" style="s2">that with static data structures we have</p>
<p begin="00:03:15.880" end="00:03:18.120" style="s2">this advantage and this disadvantage.</p>
<p begin="00:03:18.120" end="00:03:20.720" style="s2">Now, let&#39;s see what are dynamic data structures.</p>
<p begin="00:03:21.220" end="00:03:22.960" style="s2">In these type of data structures,</p>
<p begin="00:03:22.960" end="00:03:25.880" style="s2">the memory is allocated at run time.</p>
<p begin="00:03:25.880" end="00:03:28.220" style="s2">Therefore, the maximum size is flexible.</p>
<p begin="00:03:28.300" end="00:03:30.560" style="s2">When the memory will be allocated at run time,</p>
<p begin="00:03:30.560" end="00:03:32.140" style="s2">then user will decide the size.</p>
<p begin="00:03:32.140" end="00:03:34.400" style="s2">In that case, the size is flexible. Okay.</p>
<p begin="00:03:34.400" end="00:03:37.220" style="s2">Advantage is of course, <br />faster insertion and deletion.</p>
<p begin="00:03:37.220" end="00:03:40.500" style="s2">But again the disadvantage is slower access.</p>
<p begin="00:03:40.500" end="00:03:42.700" style="s2">So, we can clearly see that, there is nothing like</p>
<p begin="00:03:42.700" end="00:03:44.700" style="s2">one data structure is better than the other.</p>
<p begin="00:03:44.700" end="00:03:47.220" style="s2">The advantage of one is the <br />disadvantage of the other.</p>
<p begin="00:03:47.220" end="00:03:50.440" style="s2">So, choice of data structures <br />purely depends upon the</p>
<p begin="00:03:50.440" end="00:03:54.020" style="s2">user requirement. According to that, <br />the data structure will get selected.</p>
<p begin="00:03:54.060" end="00:03:57.520" style="s2">So, there is nothing like that, one data <br />structure is better than the other. Okay.</p>
<p begin="00:03:57.520" end="00:04:00.220" style="s2">And let me give you an example <br />of a dynamic data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:04:00.220" end="00:04:02.620" style="s2">You can see, the linked list is the best example</p>
<p begin="00:04:02.620" end="00:04:04.240" style="s2">of a dynamic data structure.</p>
<p begin="00:04:04.240" end="00:04:07.360" style="s2">We will discuss this later that <br />how linked list can be created.</p>
<p begin="00:04:07.360" end="00:04:09.720" style="s2">What are the advantages and disadvantages.</p>
<p begin="00:04:09.720" end="00:04:11.980" style="s2">We will discuss all these in subsequent lectures.</p>
<p begin="00:04:12.440" end="00:04:14.440" style="s2">Okay friends, this is it for now.</p>
<p begin="00:04:14.440" end="00:04:16.740" style="s2">Thank you for watching this presentation.</p>
</div>
